[1] Korea: duration of immunity
Date: Tue 22 Dec 2020
Source: Emerging Infectious Diseases Journal [abridged, edited]
https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/27/3/20-4543_article


ref: Choe PG, Kim KH, Kang CK, et al. Antibody responses 8 months after asymptomatic or mild SARS-CoV-2 infection. Emerg Infect Dis. 2020; 27(3). doi: 10.3201/eid2703.204543. Epub ahead of print. PMID: 33350923.
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
--------
Waning humoral immunity in coronavirus disease patients has raised concern over usefulness of serologic testing. We investigated antibody responses of 58 persons 8 months after asymptomatic or mildly symptomatic infection with severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2. For 3 of 4 immunoassays used, seropositivity rates were high (69.0%-91.4%).

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Selection criteria for this study were PCR confirmed cases in individuals in isolation in a community treatment center during the period 5 Mar 2020 to 9 Apr 2020. Those selected for the study were less than 65 years old, had no underlying disease or had well-controlled underlying disease, temperature was less than 38 deg F (100.4 deg F) with or without antipyretics (fever lowering medications) and no history of dyspnea (shortness of breath). Hence, these were mild clinical cases (51 individuals) or asymptomatic infections (7). Serology was done on all participants 8 months following enrolment in the study.

The study used 4 different immunoassays: an antinucleocapsid (anti-N) panimmunoglobulin (pan-Ig) electrochemiluminescence immunoassay (ECLIA; an anti-N IgG ELISA; an antispike (anti-S) IgG; and an anti-S1 spike subunit IgG ELISA.

Results included: anti-N pan-Ig detected in 53 (91.4%), anti-N IgG in 15 (25.9%), anti-S IgG in 50 (86.2%), and anti-S1 IgG in 40 (69.0%) (p less than 0.01).

The authors commented that while other studies demonstrated waning immunity, it may have been a function of the serologic test used in the studies, in light of the variable findings of their study over the 4 different assays used.

Choe and colleagues demonstrated waning immunity following mild illness with the MERS-CoV during the outbreak in 2015, but persistent immunity one year after severe disease. In that study, a single MERS-CoV S1 ELISA kit was used for serologic determination. It is now 5 years since that outbreak. It would be interesting to see if seropositivity persisted 5 years.

Duration of immunity will be important in deciding how often boosters are needed following vaccination. But the question to be addressed is which serologic tests would be the best for addressing this.

References
----------
1. Ibarrondo FJ, Fulcher JA, Goodman-Meza D, et al. Rapid decay of anti-SARS-CoV-2 antibodies in persons with mild Covid-19. N Engl J Med. 2020; 383(11): 1085-7. Epub 2020 Jul 21. Erratum in: N Engl J Med. 2020 Jul 23; PMID: 32706954; PMCID: PMC7397184; https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMc2025179.
2. Choe PG, Kang CK, Suh HJ, et al. Waning antibody responses in asymptomatic and symptomatic SARS-CoV-2 infection. Emerg Infect Dis. 2021; 27(1): 327-9; [Epub 2020 Oct 13]. https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/27/1/20-3515_article.
3. Long QX, Tang XJ, Shi QL, et al. Clinical and immunological assessment of asymptomatic SARS-CoV-2 infections. Nat Med. 2020; 26(8):1200-4. https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-020-0965-6.
4. Choe P, Perera R, Park W, et al. MERS-CoV Antibody Responses 1 Year after Symptom Onset, South Korea, 2015. Emerg Infect Dis. 2017; 23(7): 1079-84. doi:10.3201/eid2307.170310; https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28585916/.
- Mod.MPP]

