[C] India
Date: Fri 25 Dec 2020 14:40 IST
Source: The Times of India, Times News Network (TNN) [abridged, edited]
https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/pandemic-on-wane-7-day-average-of-daily-covid-cases-falls-below-25k/articleshow/79949650.cms


The 7-day rolling average of daily COVID-19 cases in India has fallen below 25 000 as the pandemic continues to recede in the country. For any given day, the 7-day rolling average of daily cases is the average of the number of infections detected over the last week, including that particular day. It provides a more reliable estimate of COVID trends by evening out the day-to-day variations.

So, while there have been daily variations with the case count rising on some days, the 7-day rolling average has consistently declined on all days in December [2020] so far, highlighting the overall falling trend in cases. The last time the average was below 25 000 was on [10 Jul 2020], when the COVID count in the country was steadily rising. The average fell below 25 000 on [Wed 23 Dec 2020].

On [Thu 24 Dec 2020], India recorded 23 454 fresh cases, nearly 1700 less than the tally on the previous day. At 337, the day's death toll remained at nearly the same level as the past seven-eight days although it was the highest in the past 5 days.

Although the case count has fallen significantly in Maharashtra, the state continues to report a relatively high number of fatalities. On [Thu 24 Dec 2020], it registered 89 deaths, accounting for more than 1/4 of all fatalities from the virus. Delhi recorded a rise in deaths, with 37 on [Thu 24 Dec 2020], the 2nd highest in the country, followed by Bengal (32), UP (23), Kerala, and Chhattisgarh (both 22).

