[E] Pakistan
Date: Fri 25 Dec 2020
Source: The Dawn [abridged, edited]
https://www.dawn.com/news/1597697/second-wave-of-covid-19-claims-most-single-day-fatalities


While a new strain of coronavirus has become a challenge across the globe, Pakistan reported the highest number of deaths during the 2nd wave of COVID-19, and the 2nd highest since the beginning of the pandemic, as 111 people died in the country on [Thu 24 Dec 2020]. The Ministry of National Health Services (NHS) said that it is vigilant about the emergence of the new variant of SARS-CoV-2 in Pakistan, which has been detected in the United Kingdom. However, special assistant to the prime minister (SAPM) on health Dr Faisal Sultan admitted that the situation in the health sector of Pakistan was depicting a gloomy picture. He said the situation was the 'worst' when compared to other South-Asian countries. According to the data of the National Command and Operation Centre, as many as 111 deaths and 2256 new cases were registered in a single day. Earlier 124 people had died of COVID-19 on [15 Jun 2020]. During the 2nd wave 105 people had died on [15 Dec 2020].

While national positivity ratio was 6.07 per cent, highest positivity ratio was observed in Karachi at 12.45%, followed by Peshawar 10.96% and Abbottabad 7.81%. Moreover 2361 COVID-19 patients were in a critical condition in different parts of Pakistan. According to a statement of NHS Ministry, the situation in Pakistan was being closely monitored and all passengers arriving from the UK were being evaluated. "As of [Thu 24 Dec 2020], the new variant of coronavirus has not been detected in Pakistan," it said, adding the National Institute of Health (NIH) was sensitive to and on alert regarding this new strain for its timely detection and handling.

Asked how the new variant of the virus could be traced, he said the NIH routinely did genetic sequencing for all polio virus detections. "The same polio programme staff is supporting NIH in COVID-19 diagnostics. As per reports genetic variation seems to have enhanced virus transmissibility however, it's not more pathogenic than the previous versions," he said.

[byline: Ikram Junaidi]

